{
  "doc_id": "3112",
  "text": "The function of WT ATX3 in adult brain is still poorly understood. To study the contribution of WT ATX3 protein in the context of MJD and to determine whether non-allele-specific silencing can be envisaged, we used our recently developed rat model [CITATION_1] . In this model, the expression of mutant but not wild-type full-length ataxin-3 in the adult rat brain induces a pathology mimicking the typical features of MJD. Ubiquitinated ataxin-3 aggregates are detected 2 weeks postinfection and progressively accumulate in the nucleus of infected neurons. Neuronal dysfunction with the presence of pycnotic nuclei and loss of expression of neuronal markers is observed in the substantia nigra (tyrosine hydroxylase-TH, vesicular monoamine transporter 2) and striatum (dopamine-and cyclic AMP-regulated phosphoprotein with molecular weight 32 kDa-DARPP-32, NeuN, TH) 2 months post-injection.",
